    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "See J. Pritchard, ANET, 180-88.\n16 I owe this keen insight to J. Milgrom, Leviticus 23\u201327, 2141.\n17 As recently happened to students at a major university.\n18 For a comprehensive survey of biblical crimes, attitudes, modes of punishment,\netc., see M. Greenberg, \u201cCrimes and Punishments,\u201d in vol. 1 of IDB, ed. George Arthur\nButtrick (Nashville: Abingdon Press, 1962), 733-\nG. J. Wenham, The Book of Leviticus (at Excursus I and Excursus II, pp. 281-88).\nGeneral discussion may be found in L. Bailey, Capital Punishment: What the Bible Says\n(Nashville: Abingdon Press, 1987).\n19 Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, as depicted by Matthew (who is writing primarily for Palestinian Jews\nwho have become part of the Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`-movement), is far more sympathetic to particular-\nities of torah, than he is as depicted by Luke (who desires that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` be attractive to\nGreeks and Romans) who will see aspects of torah as irrational and provincial.\n298\n[v_Lev_24_1] [v_Lev_24_2] [v_Lev_24_3] [v_Lev_24_4] [v_Lev_24_5] [v_Lev_24_6] [v_Lev_24_7] [v_Lev_24_8] [v_Lev_24_9] [v_Lev_24_10] [v_Lev_24_11] [v_Lev_24_12] [v_Lev_24_13] [v_Lev_24_14] [v_Lev_24_15] [v_Lev_24_16] [v_Lev_24_17] [v_Lev_24_18] [v_Lev_24_19] [v_Lev_24_20] [v_Lev_24_21] [v_Lev_24_22] [v_Lev_24_23] Leviticus 24:1-23\nSabbatical and\nJubilee Years\n[v_Lev_25_1] [v_Lev_25_2] [v_Lev_25_3] [v_Lev_25_4] [v_Lev_25_5] [v_Lev_25_6] [v_Lev_25_7] [v_Lev_25_8] [v_Lev_25_9] [v_Lev_25_10] [v_Lev_25_11] [v_Lev_25_12] [v_Lev_25_13] [v_Lev_25_14] [v_Lev_25_15] [v_Lev_25_16] [v_Lev_25_17] [v_Lev_25_18] [v_Lev_25_19] [v_Lev_25_20] [v_Lev_25_21] [v_Lev_25_22] [v_Lev_25_23] [v_Lev_25_24] [v_Lev_25_25] [v_Lev_25_26] [v_Lev_25_27] [v_Lev_25_28] [v_Lev_25_29] [v_Lev_25_30] [v_Lev_25_31] [v_Lev_25_32] [v_Lev_25_33] [v_Lev_25_34] [v_Lev_25_35] [v_Lev_25_36] [v_Lev_25_37] [v_Lev_25_38] [v_Lev_25_39] [v_Lev_25_40] [v_Lev_25_41] [v_Lev_25_42] [v_Lev_25_43] [v_Lev_25_44] [v_Lev_25_45] [v_Lev_25_46] [v_Lev_25_47] [v_Lev_25_48] [v_Lev_25_49] [v_Lev_25_50] [v_Lev_25_51] [v_Lev_25_52] [v_Lev_25_53] [v_Lev_25_54] [v_Lev_25_55] Leviticus 25:1-55\nThis chapter, containing some of the most theologically sensitive\nconcerns in the Bible, is set apart as a self-contained unit not only by\nits distinctive themes but also by a formal introduction (\u201cThe LORD\nspoke to Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` . . .\u201d) and conclusion (\u201cI am the LORD your God\u201d).\nThe introduction is made more striking (and unique) by the remark\nthat, on this occasion, \u201cThe LORD spoke . . . on Mount Sinai,\u201d\nwhereas the previous regulations have originated at \u201cthe tent of\nmeeting\u201d (1:1) near the foot of the mountain.1\nThe conclusion of the chapter also contains a reminder of the reli-\ngious context of the material\u2019s origin: it is part of the covenant\nbetween God and Israel that was enacted at Mt. Sinai. Thus we read:\n\u201cIsrael . . . whom I brought out of the land of the Egypt\u201d ("
